<node id="&quot;KAMEYA TOKUJIRŌ&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Kameya Tokujirō (1825–1884) was a pioneering, though now little-known, nineteenth-century Japanese photographer who learned photography at Deshima, the Dutch enclave in the harbour of Nagasaki, and later taught photography to Tomishige Rihei. He also opened the first commercial studio in Kyoto in 1862 and operated a studio in Nagasaki until his death in 1884 in Vladivostok."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-245f874840849b787c16b7dc50c295cc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DESHIMA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Deshima is a Dutch enclave located in the harbour of Nagasaki where physicians Jan Karel van den Broek and J. L. C. Pompe van Meerdervoort taught photography, medicine, and chemistry."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-245f874840849b787c16b7dc50c295cc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;JAN KAREL VAN DEN BROEK&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Jan Karel van den Broek is a teacher who taught photography to Maeda and his fellow students."&lt;SEP&gt;"Jan Karel van den Broek was a physician who taught photography, medicine, and chemistry at Deshima, the Dutch enclave in the harbour of Nagasaki."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-1e23935f45bcf7b6a4bc55e10e500a0f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-245f874840849b787c16b7dc50c295cc</data>
</node>
